postcontent: Very EARLY good to excellent condition G Series FN FAL, 7.62/308 caliber. Made in Belgium, Browning import. Serial number G666. Semi-automatic. Includes 1 magazine. Features a matching numbered upper receiver, bolt and bolt carrier. This appears to be fired very little, see photos. Some storage wear on the buttplate from and a few marks on the ejection port but that's about it. I am not dealer, this is from my personal collection so it must go from my FFL dealer to your FFL dealer. No C&R accepted sorry. Shipping is $60 to the lower 48 states, otherwise actual shipping fees will apply. Insurance is extra if desired. Certified funds only. No sales to prohibited areas. Some history: From September 5, 1959 to January 10, 1963, the Browning Arms Company, St Louis, Missouri, imported 1,836 FAL rifles in caliber 7.62mm from Fabrique Nationale, Herstal, Belgium. Subsequent to January 10, 1963, the Bureau classified this rifle as a machine gun. However it was determined that the 1,863 rifles imported by Browning would be exempt from the provisions of the National Firearms Act. Department of the Treasury Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms ORDER ATF 0 7540.1 9/11/74 Subject: CLASSIFICATION OF BELGIAN FN LIGHT SEMI-AUTOMATIC RIFLE (FAL) CALIBER 7.62mm 1. PURPOSE. This order identifies certain FN FAL 7.62mm rifles which are not classified as machine guns and thereby are excluded from the provisions of the National Firearms Act. 2. CANCELLATION. This directive cancels all previous instructions concerning the classification of FAL rifles. 3. BACKGROUND. From September 5, 1959 to January 10, 1963, the Browning Arms Company, St Louis, Missouri, imported 1,836 FAL rifles in caliber 7.62mm from Fabrique Nationale, Herstal, Belgium. Subsequent to January 10, 1963, the Bureau classified this rifle as a machine gun. However it was determined that the 1,863 rifles imported by Browning would be exempt from the provisions of the National Firearms Act. Additionally twelve FN FAL rifles were imported through an administrative error in 1974. These 12 rifles are also exempt from the provisions of the National Firearms Act. 4. EXEMPTED FAL RIFLES. Following is the final revised listing of FAL rifles, calibre 7.62mm, which are exempt from the provisions of the National Firearms Act. a. G SERIES Serial Numbers Units G492 through G494 3 G537 through G540 4 G649 through G657 9 G662 through G673 12 G677 through G693 17 G709 through G748 40 G752 through G816 65 G848 through G1017 170 G1021 1 G1033 1 G1035 1 G1041 through G1042 2 G1174 through G1293 120 G1415 through G1524 110 G1570 through G1784 215 G1800 through G1979 180 G1981 through G1995 15 G3035 through G3134 100 G2247 through G2996 750 ---- 1,815 b. GL SERIES Serial Numbers Units GL749 1 GL835 1 GL1095 through GL1098 4 GL1163 through GL1165 3 GL2004 through GL2009 6 GL3135 through GL3140 6 -- 21 STANDARD FAL - Serial Numbers Units 889768 1 889772 through 889777 6 --- 7 c. PARATROOP MODEL Serial Numbers Units 889800 through 889801 2 889803 1 889805 1 889809 1 -- 5 TOTAL EXEMPTED FAL RIFLES 1,848 5. DESCRIPTION OF MARKINGS. All G Series and GL Series FAL rifles will be marked FAL. cal. 7.62 on the left side of the receiver and Fabrique Nationale D'Armes De Guerre-Herstal Belgique on the right side of the receiver. The selector positions will be marked "S" for safe, "R" for semiautomatic, and "A" for automatic. The selector lever is designed so that it cannot be rotated to the automatic position. The Standard and Paratroop Models will have the same markings as above plus "Browning Arms Co. Arnold Mo. and Montreal P.Q." on the right side of the magazine well. The selector lever can be rotated to the automatic position but the rifle will fire only semiautomatically. 6. ACTION. If a rifle bearing one of the above serial numbers has been converted to fire full automatic, it is classified as a machine gun and is subject to all the provisions of the National Firearms Act.

title: For Sale:  Orig Springfield Armory M1D Sniper Rifle CMP
postcontent: Springfield Armory M1D Sniper Rifle that was originally purchased from CMP. This particular sniper rifle has all original sniper components from the Korean War era.The history of the M1D Sniper rifle begins during WWII. When the United States entered the war it did not have a dedicated sniper rifle in its inventory. Although the U.S. Marine Corps had a small number of Model 1903A1s that were modified for sniper rifle use, the U.S. Army had no sniper rifle in inventory and nothing on the drawing boards.The Ordnance Department realized the need for a sniper rifle and ultimately issued a contract to Remington Arms Company to develop a sniper rifle. Remington began work on the contract and used its recently approved Model 1903A3 bolt action rifle design as the basis for a new sniper rifle. The result was the Remington Model 1903A4 Sniper Rifle, which began to be issued in 1943. The Model 1903A4 was issued with a Weaver 2.75 power telescopic sight but was, in most other respects, a standard issue Model 1903A3 rifle. While the 1903A4 Sniper Rifle filled the pressing wartime need for a standardized sniper rifle, it fell short compared with sniper weapon technology at the time.NO FFL, Accepted Postal money order,Certified check.
